Perennial leguminous herbs in seed mixtures were identified as particularly important for bumblebee forage, especially for long-tongued species. One trial noted that common long-tongued bumblebee species (Bombus pascuorum and B. hortorum) strongly preferred plots with perennial wildflower seed mixes over annual forage plants (Action 19).

Natural regeneration approaches (Action 20) were found to have inconsistent benefits for bumblebees. While four UK trials found more bumblebees on naturally regenerated uncropped margins than cropped margins, two trials noted that the value was based on thistle species considered pernicious weeds requiring control, and the value was not consistent year to year. One small trial found similar bee species richness between naturally regenerated and wildflower sown margins.", "action_ids": ["19", "20", "18"]}

